### Treat-to-target monitoring and standardized endpoints

Executive summary  
Treat-to-target approaches in UC tie therapy decisions to explicit outcomes (symptom control plus objective inflammatory control) and then monitor progress using biomarkers and endoscopy as needed. AGA guidance recommends combining symptoms with biomarkers (fecal calprotectin, fecal lactoferrin, CRP) and provides practical thresholds and monitoring intervals. ŅłĆciteŅłéturn47view0Ņłéturn47view1Ņłü At the same time, implementation barriers are substantial in everyday practice (access, workflow, and clinician adoption), motivating efforts to standardize endpoints like ŌĆ£mucosal healingŌĆØ across trials and clinical care. ŅłĆciteŅłéturn37view0Ņłéturn48search1Ņłü

Why this is timely and relevant  
The 2023 AGA biomarker guideline provides actionable monitoring pathways that payers and healthcare systems can operationalize, including interval stool testing and defined cutoffs to rule in/out active inflammation. ŅłĆciteŅłéturn47view0Ņłéturn47view1Ņłü In parallel, real-world evidence indicates that adherence to STRIDE-II-style targets is often low, reflecting practical barriers (e.g., how often endoscopy is feasible, how PROs are captured, and how clinicians interpret biomarker cutoffs). ŅłĆciteŅłéturn37view0Ņłü Finally, standardizing ŌĆ£mucosal healingŌĆØ definitions is a recognized bottleneck for both trial comparability and clinical decision-making, prompting multi-stakeholder data efforts. ŅłĆciteŅłéturn48search1Ņłéturn48search12Ņłü

